This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for build-system Stage 0.

## Core concept

A compiler normally needs more than source text. A build orchestrator first decides which files belong together, which units depend on which providers and which command roots matter.

## Beanstalk boundary

Stage 0 is build-system work. It:

- reads one self-contained `config.bst`
- derives project identity, `entry_root` and `@project`
- builds canonical source ownership
- discovers normal modules, support packages and the optional project facade
- asks the compiler to prepare source syntax once
- builds deterministic project and package graphs
- schedules provider-first compile waves
- resolves narrow build-input contracts for each project or package boundary

Stage 0 does not type-check executable bodies, create HIR or run borrow validation.

## Rewrite focus

Explain source ownership versus semantic reachability, graph nodes, provider interfaces, deterministic scheduling and why config bootstrap stays smaller than normal module compilation.

Canonical details live in `docs/build-system-design.md`.
